					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">In Photoshop you could use indexed color mode with grid 8x8 enabled - this way you'll be sure that you don't add extra colors that are look the same but RGB value is slightly different, and you'll see how many colors in a tile you use.
<br />
<br />You have to use other tools to convert the graphics to use it on NES, so of course you can use them to check if your graphics is drawn correctly.
<br />
<br />I'm personally use GraphicsGale and sometimes GIMP for complex pixel graphics work. You can do it even with Windows Paint or similar programs, but indexed mode, grid, and layers are very useful for this kind of work.
<br />
<br />As I wasn't satisfied with existing NES graphics tools for Windows, I made my own, <a href="ftp://ftp.untergrund.net/users/shiru/nesst.zip" class="postlink">NES Screen Tool</a>. It works under Wine. There are few others, like <a href="http://www.romhacking.net/utilities/108/" class="postlink">Tile Layer Pro</a>, <a href="http://www.romhacking.net/utilities/119/" class="postlink">YY-CHR</a>, and more.</div>

